e images presented to us in the sources. This careful analysis of a broad range of early Irish sources demonstrates how fluid constructions of gender could be, and presents a new interpretation of the position of femininity in the thought world of early Irish authors. HELEN OXENHAM worked at the Department of Anglo-Saxon, Norse and Celtic in Cambridge as supervisor and researcher on the Mapping Miracles project. She now works for The English Heritage Trust.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemininity in literature. 0aFemininityxHistoryyTo 1500zIreland. 0aFemininityzIrelandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSex rolexHistoryyTo 1500zIreland. 0aSex rolezIrelandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomenxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500zIreland. 0aWomenzIrelandxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aIrish feminism.  aIrish history.  aIrish literature.  aacademia.  afemale gaze.  afeminism.  agender and women's studies.  amasculinity.  amiddle ages.  ascholarship.  awomen in Ireland.  awomen in fiction.  awomen's rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782046554?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046554/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles